Set-Up¶

Before any clustering algorithm is run, we need to set our data accordingly. We load all needed reviews and businesses from given and/or previous files, and begin to work with them:

  1. We find all Restaurants with either "Burgers", "Italian" or "Japanese" tags to their categories.
  2. We remove those that have more than 1 category from the above mentioned.
  3. We mark all remaining restaurants with B, I and J for their true category.
  4. We load the reviews and take those that belong to the restaurants we have gathered.
  5. Finally, we mark each review with B,I,J accordingly.

#Set Up and remove unwanted data
fixedData = data.copy()
#Set Categories as list for easier management
fixedData["categories"] = fixedData["categories"].apply(lambda x : [i.strip() for i in x.split(",")])
#Remove non-restaurants
fixedData = fixedData[fixedData.apply(lambda x : "Restaurants" in x.categories, axis=1)]

burgers = fixedData[fixedData.apply(lambda x : "Burgers" in x.categories, axis=1)]
italian = fixedData[fixedData.apply(lambda x : "Italian" in x.categories, axis=1)]
japanese = fixedData[fixedData.apply(lambda x : "Japanese" in x.categories, axis=1)]

onlyBurgers = burgers.loc[~burgers.index.isin(italian.index) & ~burgers.index.isin(japanese.index)]
onlyItalians = italian.loc[~italian.index.isin(burgers.index) & ~italian.index.isin(japanese.index)]
onlyJapanese = japanese.loc[~japanese.index.isin(italian.index) & ~japanese.index.isin(burgers.index)]
allData = onlyBurgers.append(onlyItalians.append(onlyJapanese))
allData["type"] = allData["categories"].apply(lambda x: "B" if "Burgers" in x else "J" if "Japanese" in x else "I")

Vectorization¶

Using the Sklearn's TF-IDF Vectorizer, we can group each review by its business, and sum their text to a singular giant string for each business. Then, we pass it through the vectorizer, to get a vector for each business. This is passed to both Agglomerative Clustering and KMeans Clustering algorithms to produce the final results.

Note: The values used for the vectorizer as 3000 max features, min_df of 0 and max_df of 0.5. We decided on those values after our exploratory analysis that follows shortly after. If the analysis' code is executed, the vectors will change in order to produce the needed results. This will be a problem for Part 2 if the code bellow is not re-run! Run the Vectorizer AGAIN before going to Step 2!

In [6]:
def measureAccuracy(print_results=True):
    types = ["B","I","J"]
    clusterCounts = []
    #First, count appearances of B, I and J in each cluster
    for cluster in range(3):
        clusterCount = [0,0,0]
        docs = documents.loc[documents["guesses"] == cluster]["type"]
        for t in docs:
            clusterCount[types.index(t)] += 1
        clusterCounts.append(clusterCount)

    #For each cluster, find their highest count of each category.
    #If a cluster has been nominated for a category, we ignore it in future iterations.
    finalCategories = []
    for category in range(len(types)):
        bestCluster = -1
        bestScore = -1
        for cluster in range(3):

            if cluster in finalCategories:
                continue

            _temp = clusterCounts[cluster][category]
            if _temp > bestScore:
                bestScore = _temp
                bestCluster = cluster           
        finalCategories.append(bestCluster)

    results = documents.copy()
    results["guesses"] = results["guesses"].apply(lambda x : types[finalCategories[x]])

    guesses = len(results)
    correctGuesses = len(results[results.apply(lambda x : x.type == x.guesses, axis=1)])
    out = correctGuesses/guesses
    if print_results:
        print("Final score: ", out)
        print("Found ", correctGuesses, "/", guesses, " correct.")
    return out, results
In [7]:
def generateConfusionMatrix(index=-1, name=""):
    cm = sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix(results["type"],results["guesses"])
    
    if index != -1:
        ax = plt.subplot(220+index)
        plt.subplot(2,2,index)
        plt.title(name)
    else:
        ax = plt.subplot(111)
    ax.matshow(cm, cmap="hot")
    for i in range(len(cm)):
        for j in range(len(cm[0])):
            ax.text(x=j, y=i,s=cm[i, j], va='center', ha='center', size='xx-large', color="cyan")

Step 1¶

K-Means¶

First, K-Means. With the expected clusters of n=3, we get a score of around 67% accuracy.

Agglomerative¶

Afterwards we try the agglomerative clustering, with again 3 clusters. Several linkage methods were trialed, with the best being the Ward linkage, followed close by the Complete linkage. The Average and Single linkage methods proved to not be ideal, with a general score of 33% accuracy, which is almost random for 3 clusters.

Conclusion¶

The difference between both results is on average around 2-3%, with agglomerative being the one with the highest score. We can see that Agglomerative fails to prove worthy when given less data to work with (Trials with 1k features gave 50-60% accuracy). Regardless, for the chosen features, Agglomerative is the clear winner.

Exploratory Analysis¶

The following 3 blocks of code were not directly part of this exercise, but were used to identify the ideal values of our vectorizer. Ideally, those should not be executed when reviewing the data, as they have already provided any info we may require.

By testing several values of Features and Min/Max DF, we can assume the ideal value to produce good results for both K-Means and Agglomerative.

  • For Min and Max DF, both algorithms seem to agree that 0 and 0.5 accordingly are the values that prove more fruitful.
  • As for Max Features, we sticked with the Agglomerative's decision. The reason being that KMeans provides similar results with 1000-3000 features, while Agglomerative has a terrible accuracy with 10 features.
In [10]:
#Exploration of data values - MAX FEATURES
#May take a minute. Note that running follow-up cells afterwards, will require to re-run the vectorizer above.
FEATURES = [10, 100, 500, 1000, 2000, 3000, 5000, 8000, 10_000]
kmeansResults = []
aggloResults = []

loadingBar = IntProgress(min=0, max=len(FEATURES)*3) # instantiate the bar
display(loadingBar)

for n_features in FEATURES:
    loadingBar.value += 1
    businessReviews = reviews.loc[reviews["business_id"].isin(allData["business_id"])]

    vectorizer = sklearn.feature_extraction.text.TfidfVectorizer(max_features=n_features, stop_words="english",
                                                                 min_df=0.0, max_df=0.5)
    loadingBar.value += 1
    documents = businessReviews.groupby(["business_id"])["text"].sum().to_frame()
    matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(documents["text"]).toarray()
    documents["vector"] = [matrix[i].tolist() for i in range(951)]
    documents = documents.merge(right=allData[["business_id","type"]], left_on="business_id", right_on="business_id")
    
    kmeans = sklearn.cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=3)
    documents["guesses"] = kmeans.fit_predict(documents["vector"].values.tolist())
    acc, res = measureAccuracy(print_results=False)
    kmeansResults.append(acc)
    loadingBar.value += 1
    aggloCluster = sklearn.cluster.AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3)
    documents["guesses"] = aggloCluster.fit_predict(documents["vector"].values.tolist())
    acc, res = measureAccuracy(print_results=False)
    aggloResults.append(acc)
    
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
bestResult = max(kmeansResults)
bestK = FEATURES[kmeansResults.index(bestResult)]
plt.subplot(211)
plt.plot(FEATURES, kmeansResults)
plt.title("K-Means: Best Accuracy: " + str(bestResult)[:5] + " at FEATURES = " + str(bestK))

bestResult = max(aggloResults)
bestK = FEATURES[aggloResults.index(bestResult)]
plt.subplot(212)
plt.plot(FEATURES, aggloResults)
plt.title("Agglomerative Clustering: Best Accuracy: " + str(bestResult)[:5] + " at FEATURES = " + str(bestK))

Step 2: K-Means Words¶

By using the vectorizer's vocabulary to fetch all the words on our list, and transforming the clustered datas' texts into a vector, we get the top TF-IDF scores for each word for each cluster. While the accuracy fails to impress, the words seem very well connected with their subject. Italian restaurants have words such as "Pasta", "Wine" and "italian", Japanese have "sushi" and fish related words, and finally Burgers have "burger", "cheesesteak" and "beer", all common items on such menus.

While impressive, a note to be made is that the Burger category is less specialized than the other two. The word "ramen" appears on the list, as well as several other words that don't neccecarly fit into the mix. The theory, as of now, is that the Burger cluster is not easily seperated into a whole single category by itself.

def getMetrics():
    print("=CLUSTER===PRECISION===RECALL==F1-SCORE==")
    for clusterType in ["J","B","I"]:
        clusterReviews = results.loc[results["guesses"] == clusterType]
        precision = sklearn.metrics.precision_score(clusterReviews["type"], clusterReviews["guesses"], average="macro", zero_division=0)
        recall = sklearn.metrics.recall_score(clusterReviews["type"], clusterReviews["guesses"], average="macro", zero_division=0)
        f1 = sklearn.metrics.f1_score(clusterReviews["type"], clusterReviews["guesses"], average="macro", zero_division=0)
        print("   ",clusterType, "      ", str(precision)[:5], "   ", str(recall)[:5], "   ", str(f1)[:5] , "  ")

    precision = sklearn.metrics.precision_score(results["type"], results["guesses"], average="macro", zero_division=0)
    recall = sklearn.metrics.recall_score(results["type"], results["guesses"], average="macro", zero_division=0)
    f1 = sklearn.metrics.f1_score(results["type"], results["guesses"], average="macro", zero_division=0)
    print("   ALL      ", str(precision)[:5], "   ", str(recall)[:5], "   ", str(f1)[:5])

#Step 4
def measureGeneralAccuracy(print_results=True, n_clusters=3):
    types = ["B","I","J"]
    clusterCounts = []
    #First, count appearances of B, I and J in each cluster
    for cluster in range(n_clusters):
        clusterCount = [0,0,0]
        docs = documents.loc[documents["guesses"] == cluster]["type"]
        for t in docs:
            clusterCount[types.index(t)] += 1
        clusterCounts.append(clusterCount)

    finalCategories = []
    for cluster in range(n_clusters):
        finalCategories.append(np.argmax(clusterCounts[cluster]))
    
    results = documents.copy()
    results["guesses"] = results["guesses"].apply(lambda x : types[finalCategories[x]])

    guesses = len(results)
    correctGuesses = len(results[results.apply(lambda x : x.type == x.guesses, axis=1)])
    out = correctGuesses/guesses
    if print_results:
        print("Final score: ", out)
        print("Found ", correctGuesses, "/", guesses, " correct.")
        
    return out, results

Step 4: Cluster Analysis¶

As mentioned above, the idea that the Burgers category (or even another category) can be split into more for better results is not strange. To test that, we will explore for a different amount of clusters, how good our clustering becomes.

SSE Diagram¶

Using K-Means' Inertia value, we can calculate the overall distance of each point from its cluster. By testing clusters K from 2 to 10, we form a graph showing the density of each cluster. As expected, the higher tha amount of clusters, the lower the total SSE score becomes.

However, the slope appears to be steadily declining. This does not show the Elbow/Knee Effect, proving to be non-ideal to judge the amount of Clusters we need. If we are to take something from this, is that the higher the amount of clusters, the better; therefore the clusters should be around 5 to 10.

Silhouette Coefficient¶

This time, we measure the connectivity of each point to its cluster, as well as the difference from other clusters. We want points close to their center, and as far away as possible from other. As expected, the value increases the more clusters we add, but this time we see a sudden spike around 8 clusters.

Conclusion¶

With the SSE showing no ideal results, we turn to SC to give us the results we want, while keeping in mind that the higher the number of clusters, the less SSE we have. SC spikes at 8 clusters, as well as 10, giving us the two best canditates.

    kmeans = sklearn.cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    kmeans.fit(documents["vector"].values.tolist())
    SSE.append(kmeans.inertia_)

    kmeans = sklearn.cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    documents["guesses"] = kmeans.fit_predict(documents["vector"].values.tolist())
    score = sklearn.metrics.silhouette_score(documents["vector"].values.tolist(), documents["guesses"].values.tolist())
    COEFF.append(score)
    loadingBar.value += 1

Silhouette Analysis¶

With the ideal amount of clusters being 8 and 10, we decide to explore our data with more precision. By using the following code, we can plot each Silhouette Plot for each clusters' size.

Each cluster is represented by its own unique color, while each point is represented by a horizontal line, colored according to its cluster. The length of the line represents to total Silhouette Coefficient score.

Overall, we want 3 things:

  • Each cluster to have somewhat equal amount of data
  • Most, if not all, points of a cluster to surpass the mean SC score (red dotted line)
  • We want the least amount of negative SC scores overall.

Conclusion¶

For cluster amount of 4 or lower, the negative values are vast, therefore not ideal. After 5 or more clusters, we see less and less values, with only 9 being an exception. The data for values of 6, 8 and 10 prove ideal, all having most of its data above the average line, while 10 clusters proves to be the best.

Code Source: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/cluster/plot_kmeans_silhouette_analysis.html

X=np.array(documents["vector"].values.tolist())

for n_clusters in range(2,11):
    # Create a subplot with 1 row and 2 columns
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    fig.set_size_inches(18, 7)

    # The 1st subplot is the silhouette plot
    # The silhouette coefficient can range from -1, 1 but in this example all
    # lie within [-0.1, 1]
    ax1.set_xlim([-0.1, 1])
    # The (n_clusters+1)*10 is for inserting blank space between silhouette
    # plots of individual clusters, to demarcate them clearly.
    ax1.set_ylim([0, len(X) + (n_clusters + 1) * 10])

    # Initialize the clusterer with n_clusters value and a random generator
    # seed of 10 for reproducibility.
    clusterer = sklearn.cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)
    cluster_labels = clusterer.fit_predict(X)

    # The silhouette_score gives the average value for all the samples.
    # This gives a perspective into the density and separation of the formed
    # clusters
    silhouette_avg = sklearn.metrics.silhouette_score(X, cluster_labels)
    print(
        "For n_clusters =",
        n_clusters,
        "The average silhouette_score is :",
        silhouette_avg,
    )

    # Compute the silhouette scores for each sample
    sample_silhouette_values = sklearn.metrics.silhouette_samples(X, cluster_labels)

    y_lower = 10
    for i in range(n_clusters):
        # Aggregate the silhouette scores for samples belonging to
        # cluster i, and sort them
        ith_cluster_silhouette_values = sample_silhouette_values[cluster_labels == i]

        ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()

        size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]
        y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i

        color = cm.nipy_spectral(float(i) / n_clusters)
        ax1.fill_betweenx(
            np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),
            0,
            ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
            facecolor=color,
            edgecolor=color,
            alpha=0.7,
        )

        # Label the silhouette plots with their cluster numbers at the middle
        ax1.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))

        # Compute the new y_lower for next plot
        y_lower = y_upper + 10  # 10 for the 0 samples

    ax1.set_title("The silhouette plot for the various clusters.")
    ax1.set_xlabel("The silhouette coefficient values")
    ax1.set_ylabel("Cluster label")

    # The vertical line for average silhouette score of all the values
    ax1.axvline(x=silhouette_avg, color="red", linestyle="--")

    ax1.set_yticks([])  # Clear the yaxis labels / ticks
    ax1.set_xticks([-0.1, 0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1])

    # 2nd Plot showing the actual clusters formed
    colors = cm.nipy_spectral(cluster_labels.astype(float) / n_clusters)
    ax2.scatter(
        X[:, 0], X[:, 1], marker=".", s=30, lw=0, alpha=0.7, c=colors, edgecolor="k"
    )

    # Labeling the clusters
    centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    # Draw white circles at cluster centers
    ax2.scatter(
        centers[:, 0],
        centers[:, 1],
        marker="o",
        c="white",
        alpha=1,
        s=200,
        edgecolor="k",
    )

    for i, c in enumerate(centers):
        ax2.scatter(c[0], c[1], marker="$%d$" % i, alpha=1, s=50, edgecolor="k")

    ax2.set_title("The visualization of the clustered data.")
    ax2.set_xlabel("Feature space for the 1st feature")
    ax2.set_ylabel("Feature space for the 2nd feature")

    plt.suptitle(
        "Silhouette analysis for KMeans clustering on sample data with n_clusters = %d"
        % n_clusters,
        fontsize=14,
        fontweight="bold",
    )

plt.show()
